    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "but that's just what people say to be nice, right? like, \"it gets better\" or \"you're just fragmented.\" it feels so hollow. when you look at something that's been crushed and ground down into nothing, you don't try to rebuild it. you just stop. it's not even sad anymore, it's just... logical. why keep trying to repair something that's just a void?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That logical, stopping feeling is a protective coping mechanism your mind uses to stop itself from burning out further. It does not mean your end is final or that hope is unreachable, but rather that you have reached a necessary rest point. Many people who feel \"fundamentally broken\" eventually find that their capacity to heal only returns when they allow themselves to simply exist as a person rather than someone trying to \"fix\" their parts.",
      "source": "target",
